It will "work" in the sense that it will run, but there is one specific logic error in how you are using killTweensOf that will likely cause your net to get stuck or behave strangely if you mash the SPACEBAR.
The Problem: killTweensOf(this.netTween)
The killTweensOf method expects a Target (the Game Object being tweened), but you are passing it the Tween Instance itself.
Current behavior: Because this.netTween isn't the target of the tween (the target is this.net), killTweensOf will likely fail to find and stop the previous animation.
The Result: If you press SPACEBAR while a swing is already happening, you will have two (or more) tweens fighting to control this.net.angle at the same time, causing flickering.
The Fix
Change the kill line to target the object, or stop the tween instance directly:
javascript
// Option A: Target the object (Safest)
this.tweens.killTweensOf(this.net); 

// Option B: Stop the specific instance if it exists
if (this.netTween) {
    this.netTween.stop();
}
Use code with caution.

One more "gotcha": The onComplete vs yoyo
Since you have yoyo: true, the onComplete callback only fires after the yoyo finishes (the net returns to the start).
If you want the netZone to disable as soon as the net reaches the furthest point of the swing (90 degrees) but before it swings back, you should use onYoyo instead of onComplete.
Improved Version
javascript
swingNet() {
    this.netIsActive = true;
    this.netZone.body.enable = true;
    this.net.setFrame(1);
    this.netContainer.scaleX = this.facing;

    // Correctly stop any existing swing on this object
    this.tweens.killTweensOf(this.net);
    
    this.net.angle = -45; // Reset starting position

    this.netTween = this.tweens.add({
        targets: this.net,
        angle: 90,
        duration: 500,
        ease: 'Cubic.Out',
        yoyo: true,
        onUpdate: () => {
            this.netZone.body.updateFromGameObject();
        },
        onComplete: () => {
            // Fires ONLY after the swing returns to -45
            this.net.setFrame(0);
            this.netZone.body.enable = false;
            this.netIsActive = false;
        }
    });
}
Use code with caution.

