If you want the "return" to be instant, you should remove yoyo: true and handle the reset in onComplete.
Using yoyo: true with a 0ms duration is technically possible via hold or repeatDelay, but it's messy and harder to debug. Manually resetting the angle is the standard "clean" way to do this in Phaser.
The Recommended Approach
Remove yoyo and reset the angle inside onComplete. This gives you total control over the object's state the moment the swing finishes.
javascript
swingNet() {
    this.netIsActive = true;
    this.netZone.body.enable = true;
    this.net.setFrame(1);
    this.netContainer.scaleX = this.facing;

    // Stop previous tweens on the net object
    this.tweens.killTweensOf(this.net);
    
    // Set starting position
    this.net.angle = -45;

    this.netTween = this.tweens.add({
        targets: this.net,
        angle: 90,
        duration: 250, // Shortened since it's only one way now
        ease: 'Cubic.Out',
        onUpdate: () => {
            this.netZone.body.updateFromGameObject();
        },
        onComplete: () => {
            // INSTANT RESET
            this.net.angle = -45; 
            this.net.setFrame(0);
            this.netZone.body.enable = false;
            this.netIsActive = false;
        }
    });
}
Use code with caution.

Why this is better than "Instant Yoyo":
State Management: You are 100% sure the netIsActive flag and netZone disable at the exact same millisecond the angle resets.
Performance: Phaser doesn't have to calculate a second "return" tween path.
Predictability: If you press SPACEBAR again rapidly, killTweensOf stops the forward swing, and the new call immediately resets the angle to -45 before starting the next one.
Pro-Tip: The "Cooldown"
If you find that "mashing" the SPACEBAR looks glitchy because the net keeps teleporting back to -45 mid-swing, you can wrap the whole function in a check:
javascript
swingNet() {
    if (this.netIsActive) return; // Don't start a new swing if one is happening
    // ... rest of your code
}
Use code with caution.

