The reason the netZone isn't following the "head" of the net anymore is that Zones (and their physics bodies) don't automatically rotate with their parent containers or follow the internal rotation of other sprites inside that container.
When you rotate this.net, you are rotating its local coordinate system, but the netZone stays stuck at its initial local (x, y) relative to the container.
To fix this, you need to calculate the "tip" of the net using sine and cosine based on the current angle during the onUpdate loop.
The Fix
Replace your swingNet method with this logic:
javascript
swingNet() {
    this.netIsActive = true;
    this.netZone.body.enable = true;
    this.net.setFrame(1);
    
    // Lock facing direction at start of swing
    this.netContainer.scaleX = this.facing;
    
    this.tweens.killTweensOf(this.net);
    
    const startAngle = -45;
    const endAngle = 90;
    const netLength = this.net.displayHeight - 10; // Distance to the 'head'

    this.net.angle = startAngle;

    this.netTween = this.tweens.add({
        targets: this.net,
        angle: endAngle,
        duration: 200, // Faster for that "action-y" feel
        ease: 'Cubic.Out',
        onUpdate: () => {
            // 1. Convert degrees to radians (Phaser angles are offset by 90 deg for math)
            // We subtract 90 because 0 degrees in Math is 'Right', but 0 in Phaser is 'Up'
            const rad = Phaser.Math.DegToRad(this.net.angle - 90);

            // 2. Position the zone relative to the net's pivot point
            this.netZone.x = Math.cos(rad) * netLength;
            this.netZone.y = Math.sin(rad) * netLength;

            // 3. Sync the physics body to the new Zone position
            this.netZone.body.updateFromGameObject();
        },
        onComplete: () => {
            this.net.angle = startAngle;
            this.net.setFrame(0);
            this.netZone.body.enable = false;
            this.netIsActive = false;
            
            // Reset zone position to default
            this.netZone.setPosition(-8, -this.net.displayHeight + 10);
        }
    });
}
Use code with caution.

Why this works:
Trigonometry: Since your net's origin is (0.5, 1) (the bottom), it's basically a pendulum. Math.cos and Math.sin find the x and y coordinates of the far end of that pendulum as it swings.
Manual Sync: updateFromGameObject() tells the Arcade Physics engine, "Hey, I moved the Zone manually, please move the hitbox to match."
Quick Tip for "Spamming"
Since you want it to feel action-oriented, I lowered the duration to 200ms. A 500ms swing feels very heavy/slow for a game where you mash the SPACEBAR.
